The paper deals with computational geometry, specifically the geodesic diameter of a polygonal domain. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The algorithmic approach used in the paper involves considering candidate diameter endpoints, which suggests that it may also fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of shortest path maps from vertices of the domain indicates that it may also be relevant to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The problem of finding the geodesic diameter of a polygonal domain is related to graph theory, which suggests that it may also be relevant to cs.GR (Graph Theory). Finally, the paper involves computational methods for solving a geometric problem, which suggests that it may also be relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
